'''''Music for a Time of War''''' is a 2011 concert program and subsequent album by the [[Oregon Symphony]] under the [[Artistic director|artistic direction]] of [[Carlos Kalmar]]. The program consists of four [[Musical composition|composition]]s inspired by war: [[Charles Ives]]{{'}} ''[[The Unanswered Question]]'' (1906), [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]]{{'}} ''[[The Wound-Dresser]]'' (1989), [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[Sinfonia da Requiem]]'' (1940) and [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]]{{'}} [[Symphony No. 4 (Vaughan Williams)|Symphony No. 4]] (1935). The program was performed on May 7, 2011, at the [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], and again the following day. Both concerts were recorded for album release. On May 12, the Oregon Symphony repeated the program at the inaugural Spring for Music Festival, at [[Carnegie Hall]]. The performance was broadcast live by [[KQAC]] and [[WQXR-FM]], the classical radio stations serving Portland and the New York City metropolitan area, respectively. The concerts marked the Oregon Symphony's first performances of ''The Wound-Dresser'' as well as guest [[baritone]] [[Sanford Sylvan]]'s debut with the company. 

In October 2011 the recording of the Portland performances was released on [[Compact Disc|CD]] by Dutch [[record label]] [[PentaTone Classics]]. The album marked the orchestra's first release in eight years and Kalmar's first with the Oregon Symphony. The live performances and album received favorable reviews; the recording debuted at number 31 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'s}} Classical Albums chart, and made several lists of the best classical recordings of 2011. The album earned three recognitions from the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] for the [[2013 Grammy Awards]]. Kalmar and the Oregon Symphony were nominated in the categories [[Grammy Award for Best Orchestral Performance|Best Orchestral Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Classical|Best Engineered Album, Classical]] (along with engineers Jesse Lewis and John Newton, and mastering engineer Jesse Brayman). Producer [[Blanton Alspaugh]] received the award for [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Classical|Producer of the Year, Classical]] for his contributions to ''Music for a Time of War'' and other recordings.
{{toclimit|3}}

== Program ==

''Music for a Time of War'' contains four 20th-century classical compositions based on the theme of war.<ref name=Ready>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/05/oregon_symphony_is_ready_for_i.html|title=Oregon Symphony is ready for its Carnegie Hall close-up (review)|first=David|last=Stabler|accessdate=October 30, 2012|date=May 8, 2011|work=[[The Oregonian]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> Kalmar stated that the program was not inspired by current events and that not every composition was written specifically because of war.<ref name=AskOS>{{cite web|url=http://www.wqxr.org/#!/articles/wqxr-features/2011/may/10/what-can-orchestral-music-war-ask-oregon-symphony/|title=What Can Orchestral Music Say About War? Ask the Oregon Symphony|publisher=[[WQXR-FM]]|location=Newark, New Jersey|accessdate=November 28, 2012|date=May 12, 2012|first=Brian|last=Wise}}</ref> He also warned that audiences should not attend the performances anticipating an optimistic conclusion:

{{Quote|There is redemption in our concert, but not at the end. I think that is an important point. I don't think that anybody who goes to this concert will come out and think everything is alright. I think the pacing is good because nothing is alright. If we humans have to live with war, that is pretty much what the message should be.<ref name=AskOS/>}}

The program began with [[Charles Ives]]{{'}} ''[[The Unanswered Question]]'', originally the first of ''Two Contemplations'', composed in 1906 (along with its counterpart ''[[Central Park in the Dark]]'').<ref name=Program>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/concerts/1011/programnotes/cl15.aspx|title=Music for a Time of War|publisher=[[Oregon Symphony]]|accessdate=October 25, 2012|year=2011|first=Elizabeth|last=Schwartz}}</ref> [[Theodore Bloomfield]], who served as music director of the Oregon Symphony from 1955 to 1959, conducted its world premiere at the [[Juilliard School]] in New York in 1946. The Oregon Symphony had first performed the work in January 1974, under [[Lawrence Leighton Smith]], and had played it under Kalmar in January 2007. ''The Unanswered Question'', which is approximately six minutes in length, contains parts for two flutes, oboe, clarinet, trumpet and strings.<ref name=Program/> The composition starts softly and builds with a repeated "ambiguous" question delivered by an offstage trumpet solo, answered by other instruments.<ref name=Ready/><ref name=Program/>

{{Quote box|
 |title =
 |quote = "Our program this year is a stunning, intense trip on the topic of war. It begins with a general question (that Ives did not intend to link to the theme of war), and it shows deep emotionality, sorrow, pain, harshness, brutality and peace. Not necessarily in that order, but it is a full package. A great opportunity!"
 |source = [[Carlos Kalmar]] on the program submitted to the Spring for Music Festival, also performed in Portland prior to the [[Oregon Symphony]]'s [[Carnegie Hall]] debut<ref name=Again/>
 |align = right
 |width = 400px
}}

The second composition was ''[[The Wound-Dresser]]'', American [[Minimal music|minimalist]] composer [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]]' portrayal of [[Walt Whitman]]'s experience as a [[medic]] during the [[American Civil War]]. The work refers to Whitman's 1865 eponymous poem, part of a greater collection of poems related to the conflict.<ref name=Program/><ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/music-for-a-time-of-war-mw0002216825|title=Music for a Time of War|accessdate=October 18, 2012|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|first=Mike D|last=Brownell}}</ref> Adams wrote the composition following his father's death from [[Alzheimer's disease]] under his mother's care. According to the program notes, Adams was influenced by friends who died of [[HIV/AIDS]] during the 1980s and how their struggles impacted loved ones. In his own notes, Adams wrote: "I was plunged into an awareness not only of dying but also of the person who cares for the dying... The bonding that takes place between the two is one of the most extraordinary human events that can happen <U+2013> something deeply personal of which most of us are completely unaware."<ref name=Program/> The work, which is approximately 20 minutes in length, employs solo [[baritone]], piccolo, flute, two oboes, two clarinets (one doubling bass clarinet), two bassoons, two horns, piccolo trumpet, timpani, synthesizer and strings.<ref name=Program/> In Kalmar's program the guest baritone soloist is [[Sanford Sylvan]], for whom the piece was written in 1989.<ref name=OSMay>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1011/110415_ors_may.html|title=The Oregon Symphony in May: (And One Great Night in June): A Grand Finale to Our 2010/11 Concert Season|publisher=Oregon Symphony|date=April 15, 2011|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref><ref name=OSSylvan>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/bios/guests_1011/sylvan.aspx|title=Sanford Sylvan|publisher=Oregon Symphony|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref> Adams premiered the piece with the [[Saint Paul Chamber Orchestra]] and Sylvan in February 1989;<ref name=Program/> Sylvan's performance subsequently earned him a [[Grammy Award]] nomination.<ref name=OSSylvan/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-05/entertainment/ca-571_1_american-music|title=Music : A Voice for American Music : Baritone Sanford Sylvan is at once populist and avant-gardist, dedicated recital artist and leading-edge opera favorite|accessdate=October 25, 2012|date=April 5, 1992|first=Jan|last=Breslauer|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|issn=0458-3035|oclc=3638237|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]}}</ref> The live recording sessions marked the first performances of ''The Wound-Dresser'' by the Oregon Symphony as well as Sylvan's debut with the orchestra.<ref name=OSMay/><ref name=OSSylvan/>

The program continued with [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[Sinfonia da Requiem]]'' (1940), commissioned by the Japanese government to commemorate the 2,600th anniversary of the [[History of Japan|Japanese Empire]]. Britten, a [[Pacifism|pacifist]], took the opportunity to compose a work that expressed his anti-war sentiments as well as his grief over his parents' deaths.<ref name=Ready/> The Japanese were displeased by the work's Christian connotations and melancholic tone, deeming it unsuitable for the national ceremony. Britten was unapologetic about his composition.<ref name=Program/> ''Sinfonia da Requiem'' contains three movements<U+2014>"Lacrymosa" ("Weeping"), "Dies Irae" ("Day of Wrath") and "Requiem Aeternum" ("Eternal Rest")<U+2014>and alludes to the [[Catholic Church]]'s [[Requiem]].<ref name=Program/> The work premiered in March 1941 at Carnegie Hall, performed by the [[New York Philharmonic]], [[John Barbirolli]] conducting. The Oregon Symphony premiered the composition on February 26, 2005 under Kalmar's baton; these performances marked the orchestra's last before ''Music for a Time of War''. Approximately 18 minutes in length, the symphony includes three flutes (one doubling alto flute and one doubling piccolo), two oboes, English horn, three clarinets (one doubling bass clarinet), alto saxophone, two bassoons, contrabassoon, four horns, three trumpets, three trombones, tuba, timpani, bass drum, cymbals, snare drum, tambourine, whip, xylophone, piano, harp and strings.<ref name=Program/> Its end completed the program's first half. Kalmar requested that the audience hold their applause from the start of the program until the end of Britten's symphony.<ref name=Ready/><ref name=Kozinn>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/14/arts/music/oregon-symphony-at-carnegie-hall-review.html|title=Exploring Themes of War, Both the Existential and the Concrete|first=Allan|last=Konzinn|authorlink=Allan Kozinn|date=May 13, 2011|accessdate=March 27, 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|issn=0362-4331|oclc=1645522}} Note: This review appeared in print on May 14, 2011, on page C1 of the New York edition.</ref>

The performance ended with [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]]{{'}} [[Symphony No. 4 (Vaughan Williams)|Symphony No. 4]], composed during 1931<U+2013>1934. Williams did not write the symphony on a specific subject; once he quipped that the work was "about F minor" and his wife insisted he had "[experimented] with purely musical ideas". Critics perceived the piece as a reflection of the political situation in Europe. The [[BBC Symphony Orchestra]], conducted by [[Adrian Boult]], premiered the work at [[Queen's Hall]] in London in April 1935. Boult considered this "dissonant" work, inspired by [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]], to be a {{"'}}magnificent gesture of disgust' against war and fascism". The Oregon Symphony first performed the work in February 1959 with Bloomfield conducting; prior to 2011, the ensemble had not performed the symphony since October 2001, with James Judd conducting. Approximately 34 minutes in length, it employs three flutes (one doubling piccolo), three oboes (one doubling English horn), two clarinets, bass clarinet, tenor saxophone, two bassoons, contrabassoon, four horns, two trumpets, three trombones, tuba, timpani, bass drum, cymbals, snare drum, triangle and strings.<ref name=Program/>

== Performances and broadcasts ==

[[Image:SchnitzerAtNight.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Building at night, illuminated by interior and exterior lighting, including a neon marquee sign that reads "Portland" vertically.|Portland, Oregon's [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]], where the program debuted and was recorded for album release]]

The Oregon Symphony presented the program at the [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]] in Portland the evening of May 7 and the afternoon of May 8, 2011.<ref name=BashSales>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2011/03/02/ticket-sales-show-dramatic-improvement-for-oregon-symphony/|title=Ticket sales show dramatic improvement for Oregon Symphony|first=James|last=Bash|accessdate=October 23, 2012|date=March 2, 2011|work=''Oregon Music News''|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref><ref name=PCPA>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcpa.com/events/music-time-war-0|title=Oregon Symphony presents: Music for a Time of War|accessdate=October 23, 2012|publisher=[[Portland Center for the Performing Arts]]|year=2011}}</ref> Both performances were recorded for album release by the Boston-based company Soundmirror.<ref name=Radio>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1112/120424_ors_radio.html|title=Oregon Symphony Concerts Set to Hit the Airwaves on All Classical 89.9 FM|date=April 24, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2012|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref><ref name=Soundmirror>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundmirror.com/profile/oregon-symphony-2/|title=Oregon Symphony: Music for a Time of War|publisher=Soundmirror|accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref> The Portland and subsequent New York performances were dedicated to [[Harold Schnitzer]], the businessman and [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]] who died in April 2011.<ref name=Triumphant>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1011/110516_ors_crn.html|title=Oregonians Triumphant!|accessdate=April 2, 2013|date=May 16, 2011|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://obits.oregonlive.com/obituaries/oregon/obituary.aspx?n=harold-j-schnitzer&pid=150710283|title=Harold J. Schnitzer: Obituary|accessdate=April 2, 2013|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|date=May 1<U+2013>8, 2011|issn=8750-1317|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref>

On May 12, the Oregon Symphony repeated the program at the inaugural Spring for Music Festival, marking the orchestra's Carnegie Hall debut.<ref name=BashSales/> The festival invites orchestras "dedicated to distinctive and adventurous programming" to perform "unusual repertoire".<ref name=Again>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1011/110216_ors_sfm.html|title=Here We Go Again: Oregon Symphony Will Return to Carnegie Hall for 2013 Spring for Music Festival|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=February 16, 2011|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref><ref name=Second>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/02/oregon_symphony_gets_a_second.html|title=Oregon Symphony gets a second invitation to play Carnegie Hall|first=David|last=Stabler|accessdate=October 25, 2012|date=February 16, 2011|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> The Symphony raised $300,000 to fund travel and hotel expenses for the concert series.<ref name=AskOS/><ref name=Second/> In addition to the Oregon Symphony, the inaugural festival presented seven ensembles within nine days, including the [[Albany Symphony Orchestra]], [[Dallas Symphony Orchestra]], [[Montreal Symphony Orchestra]], [[Orpheus Chamber Orchestra]], Saint Paul Chamber Orchestra and [[Toledo Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=Second/> Orchestras were invited based on their submitted program proposals.<ref name=Again/> No other ensemble presented a program themed by a single topic.<ref name=Ready/> In February 2011, three months before the Carnegie Hall performance, ''[[The Oregonian]]'' reported that nearly half of the 1,000 tickets reserved for distribution by the Oregon Symphony had been sold.<ref name=Second/> Kalmar later confirmed that 450 Oregonians traveled to New York City to witness the performance.<ref name=LookingBack>{{cite web|url=http://www.carnegiehall.org/BlogPost.aspx?id=4294985770|title=Spring For Music: Looking Back: From Carlos Kalmar|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=April 13, 2012|publisher=Carnegie Hall Corporation}}</ref>

The Carnegie Hall performance was broadcast live across the United States.<ref name=Again/> Portland's classical radio station, [[KQAC]], broadcast the concert live throughout the [[Pacific Northwest]] as part of an ongoing partnership with the Symphony.<ref name=Second/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1112/120125_ors_muscon.html|title=Oregon Symphony and Musicians Agree to New Three-Year Contract|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=January 25, 2012|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1112/120614_ors_ec.html|title=Calder to Return to Canada|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=June 14, 2012|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref> [[WQXR-FM]], the classical radio station licensed to [[Newark, New Jersey]] and serving the New York City metropolitan area, broadcast the performance live in [[Surround sound|3D sound]] in collaboration with the design and engineering consulting company [[Arup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wqxr.org/#!/programs/live-broadcasts/2011/may/12/|title=Live Broadcasts: Oregon Symphony: Music for a Time of War|publisher=WQXR-FM|location=Newark, New Jersey|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=May 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wqxr.org/#!/articles/wqxr-features/2011/may/02/wqxr-presents-spring-music-concerts-3d/|title=WQXR Presents Spring for Music Concerts in 3D |date=May 2, 2011|accessdate=October 26, 2012|publisher=WQXR-FM|location=Newark, New Jersey}}</ref> WQXR also hosted a live chat on their website.<ref name=WQXR>{{cite web|url=http://www.wqxr.org/#!/series/spring-for-music/|title=Spring for Music: A Seven-Part Series of Live Orchestral Concerts on WQXR|accessdate=October 26, 2012|year=2011|publisher=WQXR-FM|location=Newark, New Jersey}}</ref> Prior to the live broadcast, WQXR's
Q2 Music provided their own take on the Oregon Symphony's war-themed concert by airing a program with works by [[Lowell Liebermann]], Seppo Pohjola, [[Steve Reich]], [[Frederic Rzewski]], [[Dmitri Shostakovich]] and John Adams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wqxr.org/#!/articles/q2-music/2011/may/12/spring-fever-music-time-war/|title=Q2 Music: Spring Fever: Music in Time of War|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=May 12, 2012|publisher=WQXR-FM|location=Newark, New Jersey}}</ref> KQAC rebroadcast the program in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allclassical.org/assets/allclassical/modxManager/files/publicfiles/Local%20Issues%204th%20quarter%202011%20.pdf|format=PDF|page=3|title=Quarterly Issues Programming Report|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=January 9, 2012|publisher=[[KQAC]]|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref> In April 2012, the station broadcast the album recording and has since aired individual works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allclassical.org/assets/allclassical/modxManager/files/publicfiles/Local%20Issues%20SECOND%20quarter%202012%20.pdf|title=Quarterly Issues Programming Report|pages=1, 3|publisher=KQAC|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=July 2, 2012|format=PDF|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref>

=== Reception (concert) ===
[[Image:Carnegie Hall, NYC.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Image of a brown building, taken from across a street intersection. In the foreground are cars and pedestrians; in the background are other buildings and a cloudy sky.|[[Carnegie Hall]] (''pictured in 2010; credit David Samuel''), where the [[Oregon Symphony]] performed at the inaugural Spring for Music Festival to a positive reception]]

The concert program received a positive reception.<ref name=BashCD>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2011/11/24/oregon-symphony-cd-hits-billboard-classical-chart/|title=Oregon Symphony CD hits Billboard Classical chart|first=James|last=Bash|accessdate=October 18, 2012|date=November 24, 2011|work=''Oregon Music News''|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref><ref name=StablerCD>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/11/oregon_symphonys_cd_hits_billb.html|first=David|last=Stabler|title=Oregon Symphony's CD hits Billboard's classical chart|accessdate=October 18, 2012|date=November 30, 2011|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> ''The Oregonian''{{'s}} David Stabler wrote that during the May 7 performance the orchestra displayed peak condition and "played with a precision and intensity that would have been unattainable a decade ago".<ref name=Ready/> He complimented Sylvan's diction and "emotional engagement", but noted that some words were difficult to make out. Stabler called the timpanist's performance during Britten's symphony "fierce" and the orchestra's playing "clear and intentional."<ref name=Ready/> In his review of the Carnegie Hall performance, Stabler opined that the Oregon Symphony's program (which he described as one of "rage, brutality and fleeting beauty that required the utmost precision and ferocity from the musicians") focused more on playing, while the programs by other orchestras drew attention to the music.<ref name=Searing>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/05/oregon_symphony_makes_searing.html|title=Oregon Symphony makes searing debut in Carnegie Hall (review)|first=David|last=Stabler|work=The Oregonian|location=Portland, Oregon|date=May 13, 2011|accessdate=March 26, 2013|issn=8750-1317|publisher=Advance Publications}}</ref> Stabler wrote: "Everyone knows orchestras are fighting to survive, but on this night, the Oregon Symphony breathed long and deep of triumph."<ref name=Searing/> In a separate article summarizing reviews by New York critics, Stabler called the Symphony a "virtuosos band" that "now plays with more acute rhythmic precision, more clarity, more informed style... and more extreme dynamics and tempos".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/05/new_york_times_praises_oregon.html|title=New York Times praises Oregon Symphony's Carnegie performance as 'taut,' 'superb,' 'incendiary'|first=David|last=Stabler|accessdate=April 3, 2013|work=The Oregonian|date=May 13, 2011|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> James Bash of Oregon Music News wrote a positive review of the New York performance, describing it as more enhanced, dramatic and intense than the Portland concerts, partly because of the venue's superior acoustics.<ref name=Exceptional>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2011/05/13/exceptional-performance-by-oregon-symphony-stuns-audience-in-carnegie-hall/|title=Exceptional performance by Oregon Symphony stuns audience in Carnegie Hall|first=James|last=Bash|date=May 13, 2011|accessdate=October 30, 2012|work=''Oregon Music News''|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref> Bash described the orchestra's performance of ''The Unanswered Question'' as "compelling and auspicious" and wrote that Sylvan's vocals during ''The Wound-Dresser'' "conveyed the sensitive text superbly".<ref name=Exceptional/> In addition to complimenting the Symphony overall, Bash singled out solo performers by name. After noting the audience's enthusiastic response to the performance, including multiple bravos and particular recognition for Kalmar, Bash quipped "the Oregon Symphony may be regional in terms of size and budget, but they are world-class when they play".<ref name=Exceptional/>

Following the New York concert, music critic [[Alex Ross (music critic)|Alex Ross]] [[Twitter|tweeted]]: "Triumphant Carnegie debut for the Oregon Symphony -- best of Spring for Music so far. Eloquent Sylvan, explosive Vaughan Williams."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/05/crowd_critics_react_to_oregon.html|title=Crowd, critics react to Oregon Symphony's 'triumphant' Carnegie Hall debut|first=David|last=Stabler|accessdate=January 28, 2013|date=May 12, 2011|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> On his blog, "The Rest Is Noise", Ross called the Symphony's performance "extraordinary", one of the "most gripping events of the current season".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.therestisnoise.com/2011/05/oregonians-triumphant.html|title=Oregonians triumphant|accessdate=January 29, 2013|date=May 13, 2011|work=''The Rest Is Noise''|first=Alex|last=Ross|authorlink=Alex Ross (music critic)}}</ref><ref name=RossMix>{{Cite web|url=http://www.therestisnoise.com/2011/05/spring-for-music-column.html|first=Alex|last=Ross|work=''The Rest Is Noise''|accessdate=April 2, 2013|date=June 6, 2012|authorlink=Alex Ross (music critic)|title=Mix and Match}}</ref><ref name=Kalmar>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/orchestra/conductors/kalmar.aspx|title=Oregon Symphony Conductor Bio: Carlos Kalmar|accessdate=October 23, 2012|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref> In his two-page review of Spring for Music for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Ross devoted more coverage to the Oregon Symphony than the other featured ensembles and considered ''Music for a Time of War'' the festival's highpoint.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/musical/2011/06/06/110606crmu_music_ross|title=Mix and Match: Spring for Music, at Carnegie Hall|accessdate=January 15, 2013|date=June 6, 2011|first=Alex|last=Ross|authorlink=Alex Ross (music critic)|work=[[The New Yorker]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|issn= 0028-792X|oclc=320541675}}</ref><ref name=Gripping>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/05/the_new_yorkers_alex_ross_call.html|title=Alex Ross in the New Yorker: Oregon Symphony's Carnegie Hall debut 'one of the most gripping events of the current season'|first=David|last=Stabler|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=May 31, 2011|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> He complimented the orchestra for playing with "controlled intensity" and said of Symphony No. 4: "The Oregonians' furious rendition of that symphony would have been impressive in any context, but as the capstone to a brilliantly worked-out program it had shattering force."<ref name=RossMix/> The review contained an illustration of Kalmar, "hair flying and all".<ref name=Gripping/> Sedgwick Clark of ''[[Musical America]]'' called the orchestra's performance of the Williams{{'}} piece "positively searing... with fearless edge-of-seat tempos... breathtakingly negotiated by all."<ref name=Kalmar/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicalamerica.com/mablogs/?p=2082|title=Taking Chances in the Spring|first=Sedgwick|last=Clark|accessdate=March 5, 2013|date=July 15, 2011|publisher=[[Musical America]]}}</ref> After Clark's review was published, Ross posted on his blog that he and Clark concurred: the Symphony's performance was the most "remarkable" of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.therestisnoise.com/2011/07/when-critics-agree-encore.html|title=When critics agree (encore)|date=July 15, 2011|accessdate=January 29, 2013|work=''The Rest Is Noise''|first=Alex|last=Ross|authorlink=Alex Ross (music critic)}}</ref> Ross included the Symphony's concert on his list of the most memorable classical performances of 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/culture/2011/12/the-best-classical-performances-of-the-year.html|title=Outside the Machine: The Best Classical Performances of 2011|date=December 29, 2011|accessdate=October 26, 2012|work=The New Yorker|first=Alex|last=Ross|authorlink=Alex Ross (music critic)|issn=0028-792X|oclc=0028-792X|location=New York City, New York|publisher=Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications}}</ref> [[Allan Kozinn]], music critic for ''[[The New York Times]]'', considered the program "pained" and "thought-provoking", and wrote that Sylvan performed with his "characteristic acuity".<ref name=Kozinn/> He called the woodwind and brass playing in ''Sinfonia da Requiem'' "superb", specifically highlighting the "pointed" percussion in "Dies Irae" and the "haunting" string tone in "Requiem Aeternam".<ref name=Kozinn/> Like Ross, Kozinn thought Symphony No. 4 was performed "with a furious, incendiary energy" that made an ideal ending to the program.<ref name=Kozinn/>

Elaine Calder, then president of the Oregon Symphony, called the Carnegie Hall performance a "game changer". She also confirmed that the Toledo Symphony Orchestra expressed interest in performing the Music for a Time of War program in the future.<ref name=Triumphant/> In September 2011, the Symphony confirmed that Kalmar's contract, previously set to expire in 2013, had been extended until 2015. According to the organization, his contract was renewed "in recognition of his significant accomplishments", specifically acknowledging the Carnegie Hall performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orartswatch.org/news-hits-kalmar-re-ups-paul-pintarich-third-rail-bonnie-bronson/|title=News hits: Kalmar re-ups, Paul Pintarich, Third Rail, Bonnie Bronson|first=Barry|last=Johnson|accessdate=January 15, 2013|date=September 1, 2011|publisher=Oregon ArtsWatch}}</ref> The orchestra was invited to perform again at the 2013 Spring for Music Festival as one of two returning ensembles.<ref name=Second/><ref name=Fall>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/09/arts/music/classical-musics-fall-season-in-new-york.html?_r=2&pagewanted=all&|title=Striking Notes Timely and Timeless|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=September 6, 2012|issn=0362-4331|oclc=1645522|page=AR36}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://springformusic.com/oregon-symphony/|title=Oregon Symphony|publisher=Spring for Music|accessdate=November 12, 2012}}</ref> Kalmar said of the return invitation, "To be invited once is a thrill. To be invited twice is clear proof that we are in the artistic big leagues."<ref name=Again/><ref name=Second/> However, in October 2012 the Symphony announced it would not accept the invitation for financial reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2012/10/oregon_symphony_cancels_return.html|title=Oregon Symphony cancels return to Carnegie Hall|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=October 18, 2012|first=David|last=Stabler|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2012/10/18/big-big-bummer-oregon-symphony-cancels-carnegie-trip-because-of-ominous-financial-concerns/|title=Big, big bummer <U+2013> Oregon Symphony cancels Carnegie trip because of ominous financial concerns|date=October 18, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2012|work=''Oregon Music News''|first=James|last=Bash|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref>

== Album ==

{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->
| Name       = Music for a Time of War
| Type       = studio
| Artist     = [[Oregon Symphony]]
| Cover      = Music for a Time of War, Oregon Symphony.jpg
| Alt        = Album cover featuring a dark mist in the background and the text "Music for a Time of War" in red, and "The Oregon Symphony" and "Carlos Kalmar" in white; in two of the corners, opposite to one another, are logos and the text "PentaTone classics", referring to the record label.
| Released   = {{Start date|2011|10|25}}
| Recorded   = May 7<U+2013>8, 2011 at the [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]], Portland, Oregon
| Genre      = [[Classical music|Classical]]
| Length     = {{Duration|m=78|s=04}}<ref name=Liner/>
| Label      = [[PentaTone Classics]]
| Producer   = [[Blanton Alspaugh]]
| Last album = ''Tragic Lovers''<br/>(2008)
| This album = '''''Music for a Time of War'''''<br/>(2011)
| Next album = ''[[This England (album)|This England]]''<br/>(2012)
