''Music for a Time of War'' was released on [[Compact Disc|CD]] by the Dutch record label [[PentaTone Classics]] on October 25, 2011.<ref name=Management>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2012/01/oregon_symphony_management_and.html|title=Oregon Symphony management and musicians agree to new three-year contract|first=David|last=Stabler|accessdate=October 24, 2012|date=January 25, 2012|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref><ref name=Release>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2011/10/oregon_symphony_cd_release_par.html|title=Oregon Symphony CD release party of its Carnegie Hall program set for Oct. 30|first=David|last=Stabler|accessdate=October 23, 2012|date=October 21, 2011|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> It was recorded in hybrid [[Audio channel|multichannel]] ([[surround sound]]) [[Super Audio CD]] format.<ref name=BashThisEngland>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2012/10/02/oregon-symphony-to-release-new-cd-featuring-music-by-english-composers/|title=Oregon Symphony to release new CD featuring music by English composers|first=James|last=Bash|accessdate=October 23, 2012|date=October 2, 2012|work=''Oregon Music News''|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref> [[Blanton Alspaugh]] served as [[Record producer|producer]]. John Newton and Jesse Lewis were the recording [[Audio engineering|engineers]]; [[Audio mastering|mastering]] and [[Optical disc authoring|authoring]] was conducted by Jesse Brayman.<ref name=Liner>{{cite album-notes|title=Music for a Time of War|artist=Oregon Symphony|year=2011|first=Kruger|last=Steven|format=CD|publisher=[[PentaTone Classics]]}}</ref> In addition to recording the performances, Soundmirror edited, [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] and mastered the audio.<ref name=Liner/>

The album contains nine tracks (''Sinfonia da Requiem'' and Symphony No. 4 are divided into separate tracks for each movement) and totals just over 78 minutes in length.<ref name=Allmusic/><ref name=Liner/> Program notes for the recording were written by Steven Kruger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyorkarts.net/author/steven-kruger/#.UIl6RWewXEp|title=Steven Kruger|accessdate=October 25, 2012|work=New York Arts|location=New York City, New York}}</ref><ref name=Miller>{{cite journal|url=http://berkshirereview.net/2012/04/07/music-for-a-time-of-war-oregon-symphony-carlos-kalmar-ives-adams-britten-vaughan-williams/|title="Music for a Time of War" <U+2013> The Oregon Symphony under Carlos Kalmar play Ives, Adams, Britten, and Vaughan Williams on a Pentatone Release<U+2026>Highly Recommended!|first=Michael|last=Miller|date=April 7, 2012|accessdate=November 12, 2012|work=The Berkshire Review}}</ref> The album's [[cover art]] photo is credited to orchestra member Martha Warrington.<ref name=Liner/>

''Music for a Time of War'' marked the orchestra's first recording in eight years as well as Kalmar's first with the Oregon Symphony.<ref name=StablerCD/><ref name=Release/> The recording is the first of four albums to be produced by the Symphony and PentaTone through the end of the 2014<U+2013>2015 season,<ref name=McQuillen>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2012/02/oregon_symphony_orchestra_revi.html|date=February 19, 2012|first=James|last=McQuillen|title=Oregon Symphony Orchestra review: Lush, gentle strings and warm bass highlight performance|accessdate=October 25, 2012|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref><ref name=OMNRoss>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2011/12/08/oregon-symphony-cd-makes-alex-rosss-top-10-list/|title=Oregon Symphony CD makes Alex Ross's top 10 list|first=James|last=Bash|accessdate=October 25, 2012|date=December 8, 2011|work=''Oregon Music News''|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref> all under Kalmar's artistic leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1112/110831_ors_ck.html|title=Oregon Symphony Renews Carlos Kalmar's Contract|date=August 31, 2011|accessdate=October 26, 2012|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref>

=== Reception (album)===

