The album performed well commercially and received favorable reviews. ''Music for a Time of War'' debuted and peaked at number 31 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'s}} Classical Albums chart the week of November 19, 2011.<ref name=BashCD/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2011-11-19/classical-albums?order=gainer|title=Classical Albums: Week of November 19, 2011|accessdate=October 18, 2012|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> On November 19, [[BBC Radio 3]] reviewed the album on its program "CD Review", which discusses and recommends new classical music recordings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b017cffx|title=Building a Library: Walton: Belshazzar's Feast|date=November 19, 2011|accessdate=November 28, 2012|publisher=[[BBC Radio 3]]}}</ref> [[Allmusic]]'s Mike Brownell awarded the album 4.5 out of 5 stars and wrote that the Symphony "prove[d] they can easily stand alongside the world's great orchestras".<ref name=Allmusic/> Audiophile Audition's John Sunier thought the program was "well-chosen to offer great variety in sound and compositional techniques".<ref name=Sunier>{{Cite journal|url=http://audaud.com/2011/12/%E2%80%9Cmusic-for-a-time-of-war%E2%80%9D-ives-the-unanswered-question-john-adams-the-wound-dresser-britten-sinfonia-da-requiem-vaughan-williams-symphony-no-4-the-oregon-sym-carlos-kalma/|title="Music for a Time of War" = Ives: The Unanswered Question; John Adams: The Wound-Dresser; Britten: Sinfonia da Requiem; Vaughan Williams: Symphony No. 4 in f <U+2013> The Oregon Symphony/ Carlos Kalmar/ Jeffry Work, trumpet (Ives)/Sanford Sylvan, baritone & Jun Iwasaki, violin (Adams) <U+2013> PentaTone Classics multichannel SACD PTC 5186 393, 78:04 (Distr. by Naxos)|accessdate=April 3, 2013|date=December 10, 2011|work=''Audiophile Audition''|first=John|last=Sunier}}</ref> Michael Miller of ''The Berkshire Review'' appreciated the "precision and sensitivity" of the playing and Karlmar's "lucid, straightforward, and [...] virile" approach to the program.<ref name=Miller/> Miller also complimented Sylvan's performance and called the recording "memorable" and "thrilling", recommending it for any classical music library.<ref name=Miller/> Brian Horay, a classical music critic for ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', questioned Kalmar's claim that his selections should not be interpreted as political, writing that listeners "[encounter] a more difficult and nuanced 20th-century musical landscape of existential questions, gruesome descriptions, defiant submissions and cold dissonance."<ref name=Horay>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/brian-horay/music-for-a-time-of-war-grammy_b_2251457.html|title=Music for a Time of War Scores a Grammy Nod |first=Brian|last=Horay|accessdate=March 5, 2013|date=December 7, 2013|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref> Horay continued, "''Music for a Time of War'' serves as a powerful acoustic journey of peaceful resistance and questioning of power".<ref name=Horay/> Barry Forshaw of the ''[[Islington Gazette]]'' thought the war theme was "tendentious" but called the collection "enterprising".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.islingtongazette.co.uk/what-s-on/barry_forshaw_s_cd_choice_1_1197536|title=Barry Forshaw<U+2019>s CD Choice|accessdate=November 14, 2012|date=February 3, 2012|work=[[Islington Gazette]]|location=Islington, London, United Kingdom}}</ref> James Bash of Oregon Music News called the album a "brilliant stunner", mirroring his positive review of the Carnegie Hall performance.<ref name=Stunner>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2011/12/27/cd-review-oregon-symphonys-music-for-a-time-of-war-is-a-brilliant-stunner/|title=Album: Oregon Symphony's 'Music for a Time of War' is a brilliant stunner|date=December 27, 2011|accessdate=January 28, 2013|first=James|last=Bash|work=''Oregon Music News''|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref>

Soundmirror also received compliments. Andrew Quint of ''[[The Absolute Sound]]'' described the sound as "vivid, highly detailed, and dynamic" as well as avoiding "digital steeliness".<ref name=Soundmirror/><ref name=Quint>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.theabsolutesound.com/articles/music-for-a-time-of-war/|title=Music for a Time of War: Ives: The Unanswered Question. Adams: The Wound-Dresser. Britten: Sinfonia de Requiem. Vaughan Williams: Symphony No. 4|accessdate=March 5, 2013|date=March 1, 2012|first=Andrew|last=Quint|work=[[The Absolute Sound]]|publisher=Absolute Multimedia|issn=0097-1138}}</ref> Quint called the front-to-back layering outstanding.<ref name=Soundmirror/><ref name=Quint/> John Sunier said the recording's "rich surround sonics" bring together excellent performances and "first-rate fidelity".<ref name=Sunier/> He also noted the lack of audience interference, suggesting either good behavior by attendees or subtle work by audio engineers.<ref name=Sunier/> Michael Miller complimented the quality of the recording for having "no problems of intonation or ensemble" and said the album "belongs in the reference collection of any audiophile, whether they are inclined to multichannel playback or not".<ref name=Miller/> Miller specifically appreciated Alspaugh and the engineers for capturing the loudness and subtleties of ''Sinfonia da Requiem''.<ref name=Miller/> ''[[International Record Review]]''{{'s}} Nigel Simeone recommended the recording, calling it "impressive" and writing that the live sound is "exceptionally vibrant".<ref name=Soundmirror/> Kalman Rubinson of ''[[Stereophile]]'' commended the ensemble, PentaTone and Soundmirror for providing "spacious, transparent, powerful sound".<ref name=Soundmirror/><ref name=Stereophile>{{cite journal|url=http://www.stereophile.com/content/music-round-53-recordings-round|title=Music in the Round #53 Recordings In The Round|first=Kalman|last=Rubinson|work=[[Stereophile]]|issn=0585-2544|location=New York City, New York|publisher=[[Source Interlink]]|accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref> Rubinson, who designated the recording as the year's best concept album, praised the program for being "thought-provoking and restorative" and appreciated the range of emotions it summoned.<ref name=Stereophile/>

Several publications included ''Music for a Time of War'' on their lists of the best classical recordings of 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2012/01/review_oregon_symphony_and_jos.html|title=Review: Oregon Symphony and Joshua Bell play terrific performance of Johannes Brahms' Violin Concerto|accessdate=November 12, 2012|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317|date=January 15, 2012|first=James|last=McQuillen}}</ref> ''[[Eugene Weekly]]'' recommended the album as a "stocking stuffer" on their list of the best Oregon classical music recordings of the year. Contributor Brett Campbell called the recording one of the year's "most compelling", with "blistering, committed, sharply etched performances" that illustrate the orchestra's quality under Kalmar's leadership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eugeneweekly.com/2011/12/22/music2.html|title=Eugene Weekly : Music : 12.22.11, Classical Stuffers: Homegrown symphonic gifts for music lovers|accessdate=October 23, 2012|date=December 22, 2011|first=Brett|last=Campbell|work=[[Eugene Weekly]]|location=Eugene, Oregon}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[Portland Monthly]]'' included ''Music for a Time of War'' on its list of fifteen "giftable" Portland albums.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.portlandmonthlymag.com/arts-and-entertainment/culturephile-portland-arts/articles/15-giftable-portland-albums-december-2011|title=15 Giftable Portland Albums|accessdate=November 14, 2012|date=December 12, 2011|work=[[Portland Monthly]]|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=1546-2765}}</ref> Alex Ross of ''The New Yorker'' included the album on his list of the ten most "exceptional" classical music recordings of the year.<ref name=OMNRoss/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/culture/2011/12/the-best-classical-music-recordings-of-2011.html|title=The Best Classical Music Recordings of 2011|first=Alex|last=Ross|work=The New Yorker|date=December 6, 2011|accessdate=October 25, 2012|authorlink=Alex Ross (music critic)|issn=0028-792X|oclc=0028-792X|location=New York City, New York|publisher=Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications}}</ref> New York City's ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' included the album as number seven on their list of the ten "Best Classical Albums of 2011".<ref name=Smith>{{cite journal|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/opera-classical/the-best-classical-albums-of-2011-1|title=The best classical albums of 2011|first=Steve|last=Smith|date=December 11, 2011|accessdate=October 18, 2012|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|location=New York City, New York|publisher=[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]]}}</ref> The publication's Steve Smith called the collection "greater than the sum of its parts".<ref name=Smith/> James Manishen of the ''[[Winnipeg Free Press]]'' included ''Music for a Time of War'' as number three on his list of the ten best classical recordings of the year, calling the performances "superbly prepared".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/music/Music-2011-136477113.html|title=Music 2011|first=James|last=Manishen|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=December 31, 2011|work=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|publisher=FP Canadian Newspapers Limited Partnership|issn=0828-1785|oclc=1607085|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada}}</ref> The album received its second pressing in February 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/1112/120217_ors_rec.html|title=Symphony to Resume Recording Schedule with This Weekend's Concerts|accessdate=March 26, 2013|date=February 17, 2012|publisher=Oregon Symphony}}</ref>

''Music for a Time of War'' earned three recognitions from the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] for the [[2013 Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2012/12/05/oregon-symphony-in-the-running-for-a-grammy/|title=Oregon Symphony in the running for a Grammy <U+2013> update! <U+2013> two Grammys!|accessdate=January 11, 2013|work=''Oregon Music News''|date=December 5, 2012|first=James|last=Bash|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.portlandmonthlymag.com/articles/symphony-gets-two-grammy-nominations|title=Symphony Gets Two Grammy Nominations|accessdate=January 11, 2013|first=John|last=Chandler|date=December 6, 2012|work=Portland Monthly|issn= 1546-2765|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref> Kalmar and the Oregon Symphony were nominated in the categories [[Grammy Award for Best Orchestral Performance|Best Orchestral Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Classical|Best Engineered Album, Classical]] (along with engineers Jesse Lewis and John Newton and mastering engineer Jesse Brayman).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/grammys/la-en-grammys-2013-nominees-complete-list,0,7075586.htmlstory|title=Grammys 2013: Complete list of nominees|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|issn=0458-3035|oclc=3638237|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Grammy>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2012/12/oregon_symphony_nominated_for.html|title=Oregon Symphony nominated for a Grammy for 'Music For a Time of War'|accessdate=December 6, 2012|date=December 5, 2012|first=David|last=Stabler|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> Producer Alspaugh received the award for [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Classical|Producer of the Year, Classical]] for his contributions to the album and other recordings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2013/02/oregon_symphony_loses_grammy_t.html|title=Oregon Symphony loses Grammy to San Francisco|first=David|last=Stabler|work=The Oregonian|date=February 10, 2013|accessdate=February 11, 2013|location=Portland, Oregon|publisher=Advance Publications|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> The nominations marked the orchestra's first from the Grammy Awards since [[2004 Grammy Awards|2004]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/performance/index.ssf/2012/12/two_grammy_nominations_for_ore.html|title=Two Grammy nominations for Oregon Symphony|first=David|last=Stabler|date=December 6, 2012|accessdate=December 7, 2012|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Advance Publications|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orsymphony.org/news/0304/MA1204_grammy.html|title=Oregon Symphony Nominated for Grammy: Orchestra's First Grammy Nomination for Solo Performance with Orchestra by Principal Percussion Niel DePonte with James DePreist Conducting|publisher=Oregon Symphony|accessdate=December 7, 2012|date=December 4, 2003}}</ref>

